e","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
{"parentUuid":"2436ed25-40ab-4326-b85a-a0540885fc3e","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa8d8d09b1b911247","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcshWnHv5zDMRkykaFXSX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017jw9dy7ucC3BdHg165my3G","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\.pipeline\\plan.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":779,"cache_read_input_tokens":28514,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":779,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcshWkos3UgKayyTbt54k","attributionAgent":"documentation","type":"assistant","uuid":"55620138-170a-4a2f-be25-740636353074","timestamp":"2026-07-10T03:53:07.456Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
{"parentUuid":"55620138-170a-4a2f-be25-740636353074","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b6d534eb-f80d-405a-a05d-4c7eb6280654","agentId":"aa8d8d09b1b911247","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017jw9dy7ucC3BdHg165my3G","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Plan — quota administration (list + delete)\n2\t\n3\tAuthoritative brief: `.pipeline/requirements.md` (operator-elicited; Resolved / Open / Out-of-scope).\n4\tEvery Resolved item below is turned into scope + an acceptance criterion; the brief has **zero Open\n5\titems** (the operator confirmed the defaults explicitly), and the Out-of-scope items are hard\n6\texclusions that are **not** planned. Design source: none (backend HTTP API — no UI to build).\n7\t\n8\t## Summary\n9\t\n10\tMeterly already lets an admin-scoped key create-or-replace a per-customer, per-metric usage cap via\n11\t`PUT /v1/quotas` (feature \"metric-quotas\", shipped). This feature completes the quota-admin CRUD by\n12\tadding the two read/remove surfaces on the **same path**, gated by the **same** admin dependency\n13\tchain and scoped to the **same** tenant model:\n14\t\n15\t1. **`GET /v1/quotas`** (new, admin-scoped) — returns the full, unpaginated list of the caller's own\n16\t   tenant's quotas, deterministically ordered by `(customer_id, metric)`, each row the minimal\n17\t   `{customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}` field set (identical to the existing `QuotaResponse`).\n18\t2. **`DELETE /v1/quotas?customer_id=X&metric=Y`** (new, admin-scoped) — removes the cap for one\n19\t   `(customer_id, metric)` in the caller's tenant. **204 No Content** on success; **404** (standard\n20\t   error envelope) when no such quota exists in the caller's tenant (explicit, not silently\n21\t   idempotent). Query parameters only, no request body.\n22\t\n23\tThe core approach is **extend, don't reinvent**: reuse the `_require_admin_and_throttled` dependency\n24\t(auth → Tier-2 throttle → admin-scope gate), reuse the exact anchored `CustomerId`/`Metric`\n25\tallowlists PUT already validates against, reuse `scoped_transaction` (which sets the RLS session\n26\tsetting), and reuse the `quotas` table and its `quotas_tenant_isolation` FORCE-RLS policy that\n27\tmigration `0003` already installed. No new table, **no new Alembic migration**, no new cloud\n28\tinfrastructure, no new credential, and — critically — **no change to `POST /v1/events`**: deleting a\n29\tquota removes only the cap, never touching recorded `usage_rollup` usage. The scanner/auth context\n30\tstays the existing `Authorization: Bearer mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>` split-token.\n31\t\n32\tWhy this is a genuine micro-change and not a rewrite: every layer already exists and already isolates\n33\tby `api_key_id`. GET adds one ordered `SELECT`; DELETE adds one parameterized `DELETE … RETURNING`;\n34\tboth hang off the existing route module and its existing admin dependency. The only net-new\n35\tcorrectness surfaces are (a) the DELETE-not-found → 404 decision, (b) the query-param validation\n36\tcontract for DELETE, and (c) safe-error / fail-closed handling on the two new DB-I/O paths (the\n37\tgeneric `500` envelope + transaction rollback) — all three covered explicitly below and in the threat\n38\tmodel.\n39\t\n40\t## Stack notes\n41\t\n42\tAssessed each default against this project; every choice **endorses the existing Meterly stack**\n43\trecorded in `CLAUDE.md`. This is a brownfield increment onto a shipped feature, so consistency with\n44\tthe established stack is the overriding consideration and each default already fits — there is no\n45\tdivergence for the checkpoint to ratify, only the confirmation below.\n46\t\n47\t- **Language / framework:** Python 3.12 + FastAPI + async SQLAlchemy `text()` repositories — endorsed\n48\t  (matches every existing module and the sibling `PUT /v1/quotas` code this extends).\n49\t- **Database:** PostgreSQL (RDS) — endorsed; the feature reads and deletes rows in the existing\n50\t  `quotas` table using boring, proven primitives (`SELECT … ORDER BY`, `DELETE … RETURNING`). DDIA\n51\t  note: no new storage/messaging surface, so no replication/partitioning/consistency question arises\n52\t  — this is single-node transactional CRUD on an existing indexed table.\n53\t- **Migrations:** Alembic — endorsed, **but not exercised**: no schema change, so **no new revision**.\n54\t  The `quotas` table, its PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric)`, its `CHECK`, and its FORCE-RLS\n55\t  policy all already exist from revision `0003`. Adding a migration here would be dead DDL.\n56\t- **Auth:** existing API-key facade + the `scope` column (`ingest`/`admin`) — endorsed and reused\n57\t  unchanged. Both new routes reuse the existing `_require_admin_and_throttled` dependency verbatim; no\n58\t  new scope, provider, token type, or MFA path.\n59\t- **Cloud / IaC:** AWS + Terraform — **no change**. The feature provisions nothing (`iac-conventions`\n60\t  not triggered — no `infra/` resource). It reads/deletes rows in the existing RDS instance.\n61\t- **Observability / logging:** structlog facade + CloudWatch/X-Ray + Sentry — endorsed; the feature\n62\t  emits **one** new structured event (`quota.delete`) and reuses the existing `quota.forbidden`.\n63\t- **Runtime secrets:** unchanged — no new credential consumed (`secrets-management` not triggered).\n64\t\n65\t## Backend\n66\t\n67\t### `GET /v1/quotas` — the tenant's full quota list\n68\t\n69\t- *What:* a new handler on the existing `src/api/routes/quotas.py` router,\n70\t  `@router.get(\"/v1/quotas\", response_model=list[QuotaResponse])`, depending on the existing\n71\t  `_require_admin_and_throttled`. It calls a new service `list_tenant_quotas(principal)` that opens a\n72\t  `scoped_transaction(principal.api_key_id)` and calls a new repository `list_quotas(session,\n73\t  api_key_id)`, returning `list[QuotaResponse]`.\n74\t- *Why full/unpaginated (not paginated or filtered):* the brief resolves this explicitly — per-tenant\n75\t  quota counts are expected to stay small (bounded by the admin's own `PUT` calls, one row per\n76\t  `(customer, metric)`), so pagination/filtering would be speculative machinery for a set that fits in\n77\t  one response. Pagination is a hard out-of-scope exclusion. Rejected alternative — a\n78\t  `limit`/`offset` or cursor scheme — adds an input surface, an ordering-stability contract across\n79\t  pages, and tests, for zero benefit at the expected cardinality.\n80\t- *Why `response_model=list[QuotaResponse]` (the minimal field set):* the response echoes only\n81\t  `{customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}` — never `api_key_id`, `created_at`, or `updated_at`. This\n82\t  is the same minimal-exposure contract the brief pins and that `QuotaResponse` already encodes\n83\t  (ASVS 14.3.x / minimal response — threat **I1**). Returning the raw `quotas` row would leak the\n84\t  internal `api_key_id` and timestamps. FastAPI serializes the list through `QuotaResponse`, so the\n85\t  field projection is enforced by the framework, not by hand.\n86\t- *Why deterministic `ORDER BY customer_id, metric`:* the brief requires deterministic ordering. The\n87\t  repository issues `SELECT customer_id, metric, limit_per_window FROM quotas WHERE api_key_id =\n88\t  :api_key_id ORDER BY customer_id, metric`. `ORDER BY` on the two PK-prefix columns gives a stable,\n89\t  repeatable order every call (and is index-friendly — the PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric)`\n90\t  already orders exactly this way, so the sort is effectively free). Rejected alternative — relying on\n91\t  physical/heap order — is non-deterministic and would make the \"deterministic\" requirement\n92\t  unverifiable. (Collation note in Open Question 2.)\n93\t- *Empty set → `200 []`, never 404:* a caller with no quotas gets an empty JSON array with 200, the\n94\t  same \"absence is not an error\" semantics `GET /v1/usage` already uses (a zeroed bucket returns 200,\n95\t  not 404). A missing *collection* is an empty list; only a missing *addressed resource* (the DELETE\n96\t  target) is a 404.\n97\t\n98\t### `DELETE /v1/quotas` — remove one cap, explicitly\n99\t\n100\t- *What:* a new handler `@router.delete(\"/v1/quotas\",\n101\t  status_code=status.HTTP_204_NO_CONTENT)` taking the two identifiers as **query parameters** through\n102\t  a new `QuotaDeleteParams` schema (`Annotated[QuotaDeleteParams, Query()]`, mirroring\n103\t  `GET /v1/usage`'s `UsageQueryParams`), depending on `_require_admin_and_throttled`. It calls a new\n104\t  service `delete_tenant_quota(principal, params)` → new repository `delete_quota(session, api_key_id,\n105\t  customer_id, metric)`. On success the handler returns `Response(status_code=204)` (empty body).\n106\t- *Why query params, not a body (DELETE semantics):* the brief resolves this. `DELETE` addresses a\n107\t  resource; the resource identity is `(customer_id, metric)`. Putting the identity in the query string\n108\t  keeps `DELETE` bodyless (many proxies/clients drop or ignore DELETE bodies) and mirrors how\n109\t  `GET /v1/usage` already addresses a `(customer_id, metric, window)` resource via query params. The\n110\t  params reuse the **exact same** anchored allowlists PUT uses (`CustomerId`, `Metric` already defined\n111\t  at module scope in `src/api/schemas/quotas.py`) — same identifiers, same sinks, same rejection\n112\t  behavior (422). Rejected alternative — a JSON body on DELETE — diverges from the `GET /v1/usage`\n113\t  addressing pattern and relies on body support that DELETE clients do not guarantee.\n114\t- *Why 404-on-absent, not idempotent-204 (the one real decision here):* the brief resolves that a\n115\t  delete of a non-existent quota returns **404 with the standard error envelope**, not a silent 204 —\n116\t  \"deletes are explicit, not silently idempotent.\" The repository's `DELETE … WHERE api_key_id = :…\n117\t  AND customer_id = :… AND metric = :… RETURNING customer_id` returns a row iff exactly one matched;\n118\t  the service maps \"no row returned\" → `HTTPException(404, \"quota not found\")`, which the error facade\n119\t  renders as `{\"error\":{\"code\":\"not_found\", …}}` (404 is already in `_STATUS_TO_CODE`). No new error\n120\t  code is needed. Tradeoff accepted: a client that retries a successful DELETE gets a 404 on the\n121\t  second call — that is the brief-sanctioned explicit-delete contract, and it is the honest signal\n122\t  (\"there was nothing here to delete\"), distinguishable from a wrong-tenant delete only in that both\n123\t  correctly refuse to act.\n124\t- *Why 204 No Content on success:* the resource is gone; there is nothing meaningful to return, and\n125\t  echoing the deleted cap would invite treating DELETE as a read. 204 with an empty body is the\n126\t  idiomatic REST result and what the brief pins.\n127\t- *Tenant confinement is structural, not a special case:* the `DELETE` `WHERE` clause filters\n128\t  `api_key_id = :principal.api_key_id` (the primary control), and it runs inside `scoped_transaction`,\n129\t  which `SET LOCAL app.current_api_key_id` so the `quotas_tenant_isolation` **FORCE** RLS policy\n130\t  (migration `0003`) is the backstop. Because the policy's `USING` predicate hides other tenants'\n131\t  rows, a cross-tenant DELETE matches **zero** rows and therefore returns 404 — a wrong-tenant delete\n132\t  is indistinguishable from a truly-absent quota, which is exactly the desired BOLA-safe behavior\n133\t  (threat **E2** — DELETE cannot even *see* another tenant's row to remove it).\n134\t\n135\t### DELETE racing in-flight `POST /v1/events` (explicitly no extra synchronization)\n136\t\n137\tThe brief resolves that a DELETE racing an in-flight ingest enforcement is **acceptable** and requires\n138\tno special synchronization. Concretely: `POST /v1/events` reads the quota with `SELECT … FOR UPDATE OF\n139\tq` inside its own transaction. A DELETE and an ingest for the same `(customer, metric)` contend on\n140\tthat same row lock, so PostgreSQL serializes them — one commits first. If the DELETE commits first,\n141\tsubsequent ingests read \"no quota\" and are unlimited; ingests that had already read the (old) cap\n142\tbefore the DELETE committed may still be enforced against it. This is the **same replacement race PUT\n143\talready has** and is correct: the delete takes effect for everything that reads after it commits. We\n144\tadd **no** advisory lock, no serialization barrier, and no usage reset — all three are hard\n145\tout-of-scope exclusions. The DELETE's own row lock (implicit in the `DELETE`) plus the ingest's\n146\t`FOR UPDATE` are sufficient for a consistent commit order; there is no torn state.\n147\t\n148\t## Data / migrations\n149\t\n150\t**No migration, no schema change, no new stored field.** GET reads existing rows; DELETE removes\n151\texisting rows. The `quotas` table, its constraints, and its FORCE-RLS policy already exist (revision\n152\t`0003`). Therefore:\n153\t\n154\t- No file is added under `alembic/versions/` (asserted negatively by AC14).\n155\t- **No `data_protection` criterion is emitted.** No field is *stored* by this feature; the rows it\n156\t  reads/deletes were already classified **non-sensitive operational config** in the metric-quotas plan\n157\t  (`customer_id`/`metric`/`limit_per_window` are opaque operational identifiers/config, already at\n158\t  rest under RDS SSE). Recorded explicitly so security's `data_surface` reconciliation sees the\n159\t  waiver: `data_protection_waiver: this feature stores no new field; the quota rows it lists/deletes\n160\t  are pre-classified non-sensitive operational config already covered by RDS SSE (storage-level) — no\n161\t  field-level KDF/KMS applies`.\n162\t- No migration-reversibility criterion is emitted (no migration to reverse).\n163\t\n164\t## Auth\n165\t\n166\tNo auth change. Both new routes reuse the **existing** `_require_admin_and_throttled` dependency in\n167\t`src/api/routes/quotas.py` verbatim — the same composed chain PUT uses: `require_api_key` (Argon2id\n168\tsplit-token) → `enforce_tier2_rate_limit` (per-`api_key_id` throttle) → the `scope == 'admin'` gate\n169\t(→ `HTTPException(403)` + `quota.forbidden` log). This is **function-level authorization** (ASVS\n170\t8.2.1 — the admin gate) layered over **data-level** tenant isolation (ASVS 8.2.2/8.4.1 — the\n171\t`api_key_id` scoping + FORCE RLS on every `quotas` query). No new scope, provider, token, or MFA path;\n172\t`auth-patterns`' third-party IdP flows remain out of scope (this project uses API keys per\n173\t`CLAUDE.md`). GET is admin-only by the brief (no ingest-scoped read path — a hard exclusion).\n174\t\n175\t## Infrastructure\n176\t\n177\tNo infrastructure change. The feature provisions no AWS service, IAM role, security group, or `infra/`\n178\tresource, and introduces no runtime secret. It reads/deletes rows in the existing RDS PostgreSQL\n179\tinstance. `iac-conventions` is not triggered.\n180\t\n181\t## Logging\n182\t\n183\tVia the existing `structlog` facade (`get_logger(service=\"meterly\")`), OTel trace-id already\n184\tpropagated (`logging-conventions`). The facade already redacts `customer_id` (personal-data class) and\n185\tstrips control characters centrally — call sites never redact ad hoc.\n186\t\n187\t- **`quota.delete` (INFO)** — new; emitted by `delete_tenant_quota` on a successful 204:\n188\t  `userId=<admin api_key_id>`, `action=\"delete\"`, `customer_id` (auto-redacted to `***redacted***` by\n189\t  the facade), `metric`, `requestId`. This is the **audit trail** for who removed which cap when —\n190\t  un-capping a customer is a security-relevant business action (it re-enables overage), so it must be\n191\t  attributable (repudiation / ASVS 16.2.1). This mirrors the existing `quota.upsert` field shape.\n192\t- **`quota.forbidden` (WARNING)** — reused unchanged; a non-admin key hitting GET or DELETE trips the\n193\t  existing scope gate, which already logs this (`userId`, `action=\"deny\"`,\n194\t  `reason=\"insufficient_scope\"`) — ASVS 16.3.2.\n195\t- **`request.unhandled_error` (ERROR)** — reused unchanged; an unexpected exception on either DB-I/O\n196\t  path is caught by the existing `handle_unexpected_error` boundary (`src/api/errors.py`), which logs\n197\t  the full detail server-side (`error.type`, `error.message`, `exc_info`) and returns the generic\n198\t  `500` envelope — the server-side half of the safe-error contract (AC19; ASVS 16.5.1).\n199\t\n200\t**GET listing is deliberately not given a dedicated business log** — it is a read of the caller's own\n201\tconfiguration, following the `GET /v1/usage` precedent (plain reads emit no business audit event; the\n202\trequest-context middleware already carries the per-request trace). Flagged as Open Question 1 for the\n203\tcheckpoint to confirm. No log line carries usage totals or a raw `customer_id` (the facade guarantees\n204\tthe latter).\n205\t\n206\t## API edge\n207\t\n208\t`api-edge-conventions` applied to the two new HTTP surfaces:\n209\t\n210\t- **Rate limiting:** both routes are **per-owner resource** endpoints, so they inherit the\n211\t  **principal-keyed post-auth Tier-2** token bucket (via `_require_admin_and_throttled` →\n212\t  `enforce_tier2_rate_limit`, keyed on `api_key_id`) — not the IP-keyed Tier-1 (that stays the\n213\t  pre-auth edge shed, inherited by mounting). The two-principals-one-IP discriminating shape proves\n214\t  the key dimension (AC12).\n215\t- **CORS:** `configure_cors` currently allows `[\"GET\", \"POST\", \"PUT\"]`; add `\"DELETE\"` for correctness\n216\t  (`GET` is already allowed). As with the PUT addition, this is a server-to-server API with an empty\n217\t  origin allowlist, so CORS is effectively inert — the change is for completeness, not a live control.\n218\t- **Error envelope:** DELETE-not-found raises a plain `HTTPException(404)`, which the existing\n219\t  `handle_http_exception` facade maps to `{\"error\":{\"code\":\"not_found\",\"message\":…,\"requestId\":…}}`.\n220\t  No `AppError`/`app_code` extension is needed (unlike the quota `429`) because 404 already has a\n221\t  distinct code in `_STATUS_TO_CODE`. The 204 success path returns an empty body through the FastAPI\n222\t  `Response`.\n223\t- **Safe-error handling / fail-closed (AC19 — ASVS-DET T2-2):** both new handlers do live DB I/O\n224\t  (`list_quotas`' `SELECT`, `delete_quota`'s `DELETE … RETURNING`) that can raise server-side (driver\n225\t  error, connection drop, constraint surprise). Any such unexpected exception propagates to the\n226\t  **existing centralized `handle_unexpected_error` catch-all** in `src/api/errors.py`, which logs the\n227\t  detail server-side and returns the generic `{\"error\":{\"code\":\"internal\", \"message\":\"an internal\n228\t  error occurred\", \"requestId\":…}}` `500` — never a stack trace, SQL fragment, exception type, or\n229\t  internal path (ASVS 16.5.1/16.5.3). And because both service functions run their query inside\n230\t  `scoped_transaction` (`session.begin()`), an exception propagating out of that context **rolls the\n231\t  transaction back**: a DELETE that fails mid-operation leaves the target row **intact** (fail-closed —\n232\t  no partial/half delete), and GET is read-only so there is nothing to unwind. This is the exact\n233\t  shape feature 1 already proves for `POST /v1/events`\n234\t  (`test_forced_internal_error_returns_safe_envelope_and_fails_closed`); this feature reuses the same\n235\t  boundary and gets the same guarantee — AC19 verifies it on both new verbs so a forced DB exception\n236\t  is not an unverified leak/partial-state hole in the 19-criterion set.\n237\t- **Body-size guard / Tier-1 throttle / security headers:** inherited unchanged by being mounted.\n238\t\n239\t## DAST readiness\n240\t\n241\t`dast-conventions`: the running app serves these two new HTTP surfaces, so they must arrive scan-ready.\n242\t\n243\t- **Served OpenAPI schema:** FastAPI auto-generates `/openapi.json` from the routes + Pydantic schemas;\n244\t  `GET /v1/quotas` and `DELETE /v1/quotas` (with `QuotaDeleteParams` and the `list[QuotaResponse]` /\n245\t  `204` responses) appear automatically. AC17 asserts both verbs are present under `/v1/quotas` in the\n246\t  served schema so the scanner's spec matches the implemented routes (not hand-drifted).\n247\t- **Seeded non-prod test user + auth context:** both endpoints are authenticated **and** admin-scoped,\n248\t  so the DAST auth context needs the **admin** test key. `seed_api_key.py --admin` (existing)\n249\t  provisions it in staging/local; the auth context stays `Authorization: Bearer\n250\t  mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>` — the existing DAST-3 context, documented here so\n251\t  `test_dast_context_documented.py` stays green (it greps the plan/docs for `mtr_live` + `Bearer`).\n252\t\n253\t## Input surface (enumerated for security's `input_surface` reconciliation)\n254\t\n255\tEvery input source the feature exposes, with its planned controls:\n256\t\n257\t1. **`GET /v1/quotas`** — accepts **no** body/query/path parameter (full list, no filter/pagination —\n258\t   a hard exclusion). Its only input is the reused, unchanged `Authorization` header. **Validation\n259\t   AC: N/A** (no request parameter to validate). **Rate-limit:** Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` (reused) →\n260\t   AC12. Authorization/scope covered by AC4; auth by AC5.\n261\t2. **`DELETE /v1/quotas` query parameters** (new): `customer_id`, `metric`; unknown query params\n262\t   rejected (`extra='forbid'`). **Validation AC (non-waivable):** AC9. **Rate-limit:** Tier-2\n263\t   per-`api_key_id` (reused) → AC12.\n264\t3. **`Authorization` header** (unchanged): the existing anchored split-token regex in\n265\t   `src/auth/api_key.py` — reused, not modified.\n266\t\n267\tNo queue/message consumer, file/CSV ingest, form, or webhook receiver is introduced.\n268\t\n269\t## Files affected\n270\t\n271\tModify (source + tests — the implementation change set):\n272\t- `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` — add `QuotaDeleteParams` (query-param contract; reuse the module-level\n273\t  `CustomerId`/`Metric`; `ConfigDict(extra='forbid')`). `QuotaResponse` reused unchanged for GET rows.\n274\t- `src/api/routes/quotas.py` — add the `GET` (list) and `DELETE` handlers; both depend on the existing\n275\t  `_require_admin_and_throttled`.\n276\t- `src/services/quota_service.py` — add `list_tenant_quotas(principal)` (read + map to\n277\t  `list[QuotaResponse]`) and `delete_tenant_quota(principal, params)` (delete, raise 404 if absent,\n278\t  emit `quota.delete`).\n279\t- `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py` — add `list_quotas(session, api_key_id)` (ordered, `api_key_id`-\n280\t  scoped `SELECT`) and `delete_quota(session, api_key_id, customer_id, metric)` (parameterized\n281\t  `DELETE … RETURNING`, returns whether a row matched).\n282\t- `src/api/middleware.py` — add `\"DELETE\"` to the CORS `allow_methods` list.\n283\t- `tests/test_schemas_quotas.py` — unit tests for `QuotaDeleteParams` (allowlist accept/reject,\n284\t  injection/oversized rejection, `extra='forbid'`).\n285\t\n286\tCreate:\n287\t- `tests/integration/test_quotas_list_delete.py` — integration tests for GET (order, minimal fields,\n288\t  empty→`200 []`, tenant isolation, ingest-key 403, no-auth 401) and DELETE (204 + row removed, 404\n289\t  absent, cross-tenant→404 + victim row intact, validation 422, ingest-key 403, no-auth 401,\n290\t  `quota.delete` logged), the Tier-2 two-principals-one-IP shape, the no-usage-reset / no-events-change\n291\t  guarantee, the safe-error / fail-closed 500 path on GET and DELETE (AC19), and the OpenAPI presence\n292\t  of both verbs.\n293\t\n294\tDocs (handled at the documentation stage, per the \"docs updated for touched directories\"\n295\tdone-criterion — not part of the implementation change set):\n296\t- `docs/system_architecture.md` — add the GET/DELETE quota-admin surface (also carries the\n297\t  `mtr_live`/`Bearer` DAST-3 context string).\n298\t- `src/api/README.md`, `src/services/README.md`, `src/repositories/README.md` — per-directory updates\n299\t  for the touched modules.\n300\t- `CLAUDE.md` — note `GET`/`DELETE /v1/quotas` alongside the existing `PUT` in the auth line.\n301\t\n302\t**Task decomposition:** the implementation change set is **7 files** (6 modified + 1 created source/\n303\ttest files above; docs are a separate stage). That is below the ≥8-file threshold, so **no\n304\t`tasks.md`** is emitted — this builds single-shot from `plan.md`, extending existing modules with a\n305\trepo function pair, a service function pair, two route handlers, and one query-param schema.\n306\t\n307\t## Test strategy\n308\t\n309\t**`pyramid`** (the project default). The unit tier carries the boundary logic that needs no database:\n310\t`QuotaDeleteParams` validation (allowlist, injection/oversized rejection, `extra='forbid'`) in\n311\t`tests/test_schemas_quotas.py`, and the 404-vs-204 decision is a thin mapping best proven end-to-end.\n312\tA **focused integration tier** against the real Postgres + Redis testcontainers (existing `conftest`)\n313\tcovers the guarantees that are only real against actual Postgres — deterministic ordering over a\n314\tseeded multi-row set, the empty-list case, tenant isolation for both GET and DELETE (the FORCE-RLS\n315\tbackstop + `api_key_id` filter), the DELETE 204/404 contract, the safe-error / fail-closed 500 path\n316\t(forced internal error → generic envelope, no partial delete), the two-principals-one-IP throttle\n317\tdimension, and the \"delete removes the cap but never resets `usage_rollup`, and `POST /v1/events`\n318\tun-caps cleanly\" cross-behavior. E2E stays minimal (the route round-trips are the integration tier).\n319\tThis is a bias toward exercising the real datastore for the tenancy/ordering guarantees, still under\n320\tthe unchanged `>= 85%` branch-coverage gate — not a relaxation of it.\n321\t\n322\t## Open questions\n323\t\n324\t1. **GET list read-logging.** The plan emits **no** dedicated business-audit log for `GET /v1/quotas`\n325\t   (a read of the caller's own config; mirrors `GET /v1/usage`, which logs no business event). DELETE\n326\t   *is* logged (`quota.delete`). *Proposed default:* keep GET unlogged. Confirm at the checkpoint, or\n327\t   add a light `quota.list` INFO (count only, no `customer_id`) if admin-read auditing is desired.\n328\t2. **Ordering collation.** `ORDER BY customer_id, metric` yields a **deterministic** order every call\n329\t   (the requirement), using the RDS default text collation. *Proposed default:* do not add\n330\t   `COLLATE \"C\"` — the requirement is *deterministic* order (guaranteed by `ORDER BY`), not\n331\t   byte-identical order across differing collations, and there is a single RDS collation in this\n332\t   deployment. Confirm, or add `COLLATE \"C\"` if cross-environment byte-stable ordering is later\n333\t   required.\n334\t\n335\t## Threat Model\n336\t\n337\tMethod: STRIDE (Shostack), scoped to **this feature** (GET list + DELETE). Each credible threat names\n338\ta **concrete mechanism** (library/config/SQL construct + the file it lives in) and the **ASVS 5.0.0**\n339\trequirement it satisfies. Most controls are **reused, already-verified** mechanisms from the shipped\n340\tmetric-quotas feature; the net-new surfaces are the DELETE query-param contract, the DELETE-not-found\n341\tpath, and the safe-error / fail-closed handling on the two new DB-I/O paths.\n342\t\n343\t### Assets and trust boundaries\n344\t\n345\tAssets: the `quotas` rows (now *readable* via GET and *removable* via DELETE), the `api_keys.scope`\n346\tauthorization attribute, the `usage_rollup` counters (which DELETE must **not** touch), the admin API\n347\tkey (Argon2id-hashed secret), and the `GET`/`DELETE /v1/quotas` endpoints. Trust boundaries crossed:\n348\t**client ↔ app** (public internet → ALB → FastAPI: unauthenticated bytes become an authenticated,\n349\tscope-bearing principal) and **app ↔ RDS** (the scoped transaction that lists or deletes a tenant's\n350\trows). No new service↔service or cloud-control-plane boundary is introduced.\n351\t\n352\t### Validation contracts (per boundary input)\n353\t\n354\t| Input | Contract (type + bound + allowlist) | Sink it protects | Lives in |\n355\t|---|---|---|---|\n356\t| `customer_id` (DELETE query) | `constr(pattern=r'^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]{1,128}$')` (reused module `CustomerId`); anchored allowlist, ReDoS-safe | the `DELETE … WHERE customer_id = :customer_id` SQL | `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` |\n357\t| `metric` (DELETE query) | `constr(pattern=r'^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]{1,64}$')` (reused module `Metric`); anchored allowlist | the `DELETE … WHERE metric = :metric` SQL | `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` |\n358\t| unknown DELETE query params | `ConfigDict(extra='forbid')` on `QuotaDeleteParams` | mass-assignment / no client-set `api_key_id` | `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` |\n359\t| `GET /v1/quotas` | no request parameter accepted (no body/query/path) — no injectable input | n/a (only the `api_key_id`-scoped list `SELECT`) | `src/api/routes/quotas.py` |\n360\t| `Authorization` header | existing anchored `^mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>$` regex | `api_keys` lookup | `src/auth/api_key.py` (unchanged) |\n361\t\n362\tAll new SQL (the list `SELECT` and the `DELETE`) uses SQLAlchemy `text()` with **bound parameters\n363\tonly** — no string interpolation (ASVS 1.2.4).\n364\t\n365\t### STRIDE table\n366\t\n367\t| Category | Asset / Boundary | Attack vector | Severity | Mitigation (mechanism + file) | ASVS req(s) |\n368\t|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n369\t| **Spoofing** | GET/DELETE `/v1/quotas` / client↔app | Unauthenticated or non-admin caller lists or deletes caps | High | Reused `_require_admin_and_throttled`: `require_api_key` (Argon2id split-token) then a `scope == 'admin'` assertion raising `HTTPException(403)` — `src/api/routes/quotas.py` + `src/auth/api_key.py` | 6.2.x, 8.2.1 |\n370\t| **Tampering** | DELETE SQL / client↔app | SQLi via `customer_id`/`metric` query params into the new `DELETE` | High | Anchored allowlist `constr` on `QuotaDeleteParams` (`src/api/schemas/quotas.py`) rejects at the boundary (422) + parameterized `text()` bind params in `delete_quota` (`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`) — payload never reaches the sink | 1.2.4, 2.2.1 |\n371\t| **Tampering** | DELETE params / mass-assignment | Client injects an extra query param (e.g. `api_key_id`) to widen the delete | Medium | `ConfigDict(extra='forbid')` on `QuotaDeleteParams`; `api_key_id` is set server-side from the principal, never a query param — `src/api/schemas/quotas.py`, `src/services/quota_service.py` | 15.3.3, 8.2.3 |\n372\t| **Repudiation** | admin delete / audit | Admin denies removing a cap (un-capping a customer re-enables overage) | Medium | Structured `quota.delete` INFO (`userId`, `action=\"delete\"`, `customer_id` [facade-redacted], `metric`, `requestId`) via the structlog facade; `requestId` ties the 204/404 response to the log line — `src/services/quota_service.py` | 16.2.1 |\n373\t| **Info Disclosure** | GET response / client↔app | List leaks internal fields (`api_key_id`, timestamps) or another tenant's caps | High | `response_model=list[QuotaResponse]` projects only `{customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}` (FastAPI-enforced); the list `SELECT` filters `api_key_id = :principal.api_key_id` + FORCE-RLS backstop — `src/api/routes/quotas.py`, `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`, `alembic/versions/0003_*` | 14.3.x, 8.2.2 |\n374\t| **Info Disclosure** | GET/DELETE DB I/O / app↔RDS | A forced/unexpected server-side error (DB driver/connection exception mid-`SELECT` or mid-`DELETE`) leaks a stack trace, SQL fragment, exception type, or internal path in the response; or a DELETE half-applies leaving inconsistent state | Medium | Reused centralized `handle_unexpected_error` catch-all returns the generic `{code:internal}` `500` envelope (detail logged server-side via `request.unhandled_error`, **never** in the response body) — no stack/SQL/type/path leak; both service paths run inside `scoped_transaction`, so a raised exception rolls the transaction back (**fail-closed — no partial DELETE; GET is read-only**). Verified by AC19, mirroring feature 1's `POST /v1/events` precedent — `src/api/errors.py`, `src/services/quota_service.py`, `src/db/session.py` | 16.5.1, 16.5.3 |\n375\t| **Info Disclosure** | DELETE query string | `customer_id`/`metric` in the URL query string may land in ALB/proxy access logs | Low (accepted) | Mirrors the existing `GET /v1/usage` query-param contract (the caller's *own* opaque identifiers); app-side structured logs **redact** `customer_id` via the logging facade; ALB access-log exposure of a caller's own id is a pre-existing, accepted risk — `src/logging/__init__.py` | 14.3.x |\n376\t| **Denial of Service** | both endpoints | Request flood spends Argon2id verifies / DB work | Medium | Reused Tier-1 IP+route pre-auth throttle (`Tier1EdgeThrottleMiddleware`, `/health` exempt, client IP from `request.client` behind the ALB) + Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` post-auth token bucket (`enforce_tier2_rate_limit`) on both routes — `src/api/middleware.py`, `src/auth/rate_limit.py` | 2.4.1, 4.x |\n377\t| **Denial of Service** | GET list size | Unpaginated list grows expensive if a tenant accumulates many quotas | Low (accepted) | Per-tenant quota counts are bounded by admin `PUT` volume (brief: \"expected to stay small\"); the `SELECT` is a PK-prefix-ordered index scan scoped to one `api_key_id`; Tier-2 throttle bounds call rate — `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py` | 4.x |\n378\t| **Elevation of Privilege** | GET/DELETE (function-level) | `ingest`-scoped key calls the admin-only routes | High | Reused `scope == 'admin'` gate → `HTTPException(403)`; `quota.forbidden` logged — `src/api/routes/quotas.py` | 8.2.1 |\n379\t| **Elevation of Privilege** | `quotas` (data-level / IDOR/BOLA) | A key lists or **deletes** another tenant's cap | High | Every `quotas` query filters `api_key_id = :principal.api_key_id`; `quotas_tenant_isolation` **FORCE** RLS policy via `SET LOCAL app.current_api_key_id` in `scoped_transaction`. **Enabling condition (U-02):** `quotas` is owned by the `meterly_app` role, so `FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` (already set in migration `0003`) is required and present — a table owner bypasses non-FORCE RLS. A cross-tenant DELETE therefore matches zero rows → 404 (cannot see or remove another tenant's row) — `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`, `src/db/session.py`, `alembic/versions/0003_*` | 8.2.2, 8.4.1 |\n380\t| **Tampering** | `usage_rollup` integrity | DELETE resets/corrupts recorded usage, or races ingest into torn state | Medium (accepted) | `delete_quota` issues **only** a `DELETE` on `quotas` — it never touches `usage_rollup` (no usage reset, a hard exclusion). The DELETE's implicit row lock and the ingest's `SELECT … FOR UPDATE OF q` serialize on the same quota row, giving a consistent commit order without added synchronization (brief-accepted) — `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py` | 2.3.x |\n381\t\n382\t### Accepted risks / out of scope\n383\t\n384\t- **DELETE-vs-ingest race** is accepted with **no** added synchronization (brief): the shared row lock\n385\t  yields a consistent commit order; enforcement stops for everything that reads after the delete\n386\t  commits, matching PUT-replacement semantics. Not a concurrency-integrity guarantee this slice.\n387\t- **`customer_id` in the DELETE query string** (Low): consistent with the existing `GET /v1/usage`\n388\t  query-param design; app logs redact it; ALB access-log exposure of a caller's own id is accepted.\n389\t- **Unpaginated GET list size** (Low): accepted on the brief's \"counts stay small\" assumption; Tier-2\n390\t  throttle + index scan bound it.\n391\t- **Quota data at rest** relies on RDS SSE (non-sensitive classification) — no field-level crypto;\n392\t  this feature stores no new field.\n393\t- **Hard exclusions not modeled:** pagination/filtering on GET, ingest-scoped read of quotas,\n394\t  including usage/remaining in the list, usage reset on delete, any `POST /v1/events` behavior change,\n395\t  and blocking/serializing delete against ingest — all out of scope per the brief.\n396\t\n397\t### Threat-model diagram (Mermaid DFD)\n398\t\n399\t```mermaid\n400\tflowchart TD\n401\t    admin[Admin API client]:::ext\n402\t    subgraph edge[Trust boundary: public edge - ALB to FastAPI]\n403\t        t1(Tier-1 IP throttle + body guard)\n404\t        auth(require_api_key + Tier-2 throttle)\n405\t        scope(admin-scope gate):::warn\n406\t        getq(GET /v1/quotas handler)\n407\t        delq(DELETE /v1/quotas handler):::warn\n408\t        err(handle_unexpected_error - generic 500 envelope)\n409\t    end\n410\t    subgraph rds[Trust boundary: app to RDS Postgres - RLS FORCE]\n411\t        keys[(api_keys + scope)]\n412\t        quotas[(quotas)]\n413\t        rollup[(usage_rollup - untouched)]\n414\t    end\n415\t    redis[(Redis token buckets)]\n416\t\n417\t    admin -- HTTPS Bearer mtr_live_key -->|DELETE query customer_id,metric| t1\n418\t    t1 -- rate ok --> auth\n419\t    auth -. verify Argon2id .-> keys\n420\t    auth -. token bucket .-> redis\n421\t    auth --> scope\n422\t    scope -- scope=admin --> getq\n423\t    scope -- scope=admin --> delq\n424\t    getq -- SELECT api_key_id-scoped ORDER BY --> quotas\n425\t    delq -- DELETE api_key_id-scoped RETURNING --> quotas\n426\t    getq -. DB error .-> err\n427\t    delq -. DB error - txn rollback, no partial delete .-> err\n428\t    delq -. never writes .-x rollup\n429\t\n430\t    classDef ext fill:#eee,stroke:#333;\n431\t    classDef warn fill:#ffe0b2,stroke:#b71c1c,stroke-width:2px;\n432\t```\n433\t\n434\t⚠ high-risk nodes: the **admin-scope gate** (Spoofing/EoP) and the **DELETE handler** (cross-tenant\n435\tIDOR/BOLA — mitigated by the `api_key_id` filter + FORCE RLS, so a wrong-tenant delete matches zero\n436\trows → 404). A forced DB error on either path lands at the generic-500 boundary (no leak, txn\n437\trolled back — AC19).\n438\t\n439\t### Copy-paste visualization prompt\n440\t\n441\t```text\n442\tBuild a threat-model visualization for this feature (Meterly quota administration: list + delete).\n443\t\n444\tASSETS: quotas rows (per-tenant caps: api_key_id, customer_id, metric, limit_per_window), now\n445\treadable via GET and removable via DELETE; api_keys.scope authorization attribute; usage_rollup\n446\thourly counters (which DELETE must NOT touch); the admin API key (Argon2id-hashed split token); the\n447\tGET /v1/quotas and DELETE /v1/quotas HTTP endpoints.\n448\t\n449\tTRUST BOUNDARIES: (1) client <-> app: public internet -> ALB -> FastAPI, where unauthenticated bytes\n450\tbecome an authenticated, admin-scope-bearing principal; (2) app <-> RDS PostgreSQL: the scoped\n451\ttransaction that lists or deletes a tenant's quota rows, with a FORCE row-level-security policy\n452\t(quotas_tenant_isolation) as the backstop behind the explicit api_key_id filter.\n453\t\n454\tSTRIDE THREATS (threat; vector; severity; mitigation + concrete mechanism):\n455\t- Spoofing; unauthenticated/non-admin caller lists or deletes caps; HIGH; reused\n456\t  _require_admin_and_throttled = require_api_key (Argon2id split token) + admin-scope assertion\n457\t  raising HTTP 403.\n458\t- Tampering; SQL injection via customer_id/metric DELETE query params; HIGH; anchored allowlist\n459\t  constr on QuotaDeleteParams rejects at the boundary (422) + parameterized SQLAlchemy text() bind\n460\t  params only.\n461\t- Tampering; extra query param to widen the delete (mass-assignment); MEDIUM; Pydantic\n462\t  extra='forbid'; api_key_id set server-side from the principal, never a query param.\n463\t- Repudiation; admin denies removing a cap (un-capping re-enables overage); MEDIUM; structured\n464\t  quota.delete INFO log (userId, action=delete, customer_id [redacted], metric, requestId).\n465\t- Information disclosure; GET leaks internal fields or another tenant's caps; HIGH;\n466\t  response_model=list[QuotaResponse] minimal field set + api_key_id-scoped SELECT + FORCE RLS.\n467\t- Information disclosure / safe-error; a forced server-side error (DB driver/connection exception) on\n468\t  GET or DELETE leaks a stack trace/SQL/exception type/internal path, or a DELETE half-applies;\n469\t  MEDIUM; centralized handle_unexpected_error catch-all returns the generic {code:internal} 500\n470\t  envelope (detail logged server-side only, no leak); both paths run inside scoped_transaction so a\n471\t  raised exception rolls the transaction back (fail-closed, no partial DELETE; GET is read-only).\n472\t- Information disclosure; customer_id/metric in the DELETE query string may reach access logs; LOW\n473\t  (accepted); mirrors GET /v1/usage; app logs redact customer_id; ALB log exposure of own id\n474\t  accepted.\n475\t- Denial of service; request flood; MEDIUM; reused Tier-1 IP throttle + Tier-2 per-api_key_id token\n476\t  bucket + body-size guard.\n477\t- Denial of service; unpaginated GET list grows expensive; LOW (accepted); per-tenant counts stay\n478\t  small; PK-prefix index scan scoped to one api_key_id; Tier-2 throttle bounds call rate.\n479\t- Elevation of privilege; ingest-scoped key calls the admin-only routes; HIGH; scope=='admin' gate\n480\t  -> HTTP 403.\n481\t- Elevation of privilege; a key lists or deletes another tenant's cap (IDOR/BOLA); HIGH; every query\n482\t  filters api_key_id = principal.api_key_id; FORCE RLS quotas_tenant_isolation via SET LOCAL\n483\t  app.current_api_key_id (FORCE required because meterly_app owns the table) -> cross-tenant DELETE\n484\t  matches zero rows -> 404.\n485\t- Tampering; DELETE resets usage or races ingest into torn state; MEDIUM (accepted); delete_quota\n486\t  only DELETEs quotas, never touches usage_rollup; shared row lock with the ingest FOR UPDATE gives\n487\t  a consistent commit order without added synchronization.\n488\t\n489\tRender this as an OWASP Threat Dragon diagram. Output either (a) valid Threat Dragon JSON importable\n490\tat app.threatdragon.com, or (b) a labeled data flow diagram with trust boundaries if JSON is not\n491\tfeasible. No additional context is available beyond what is in this prompt.\n492\t```\n493\t\n494\t## ASVS Compliance\n495\t\n496\tOWASP ASVS 5.0.0. **L1 + L2 are universal** for every triggered chapter; in-scope **L3** is listed\n497\tbelow. Requirement IDs are cited per threat in the STRIDE table above.\n498\t\n499\t**Triggered chapters:** V1 (encoding / parameterized SQL — the DELETE `text()` bind params), V2\n500\t(validation — the `QuotaDeleteParams` contract + anti-automation Tier-2 throttle), V4 (API surface —\n501\ttwo new verbs on `/v1/quotas`), V6 (API-key authentication — reused), V8 (authorization — the admin\n502\tgate + tenant isolation on read/delete; **the priority chapter for this slice** given DELETE's\n503\tcross-tenant BOLA risk), V12 (TLS — existing ALB/RDS TLS, unchanged), V13 (config — docs off in prod,\n504\tsecrets in manager — existing), V14 (data protection — minimal GET response, no sensitive data\n505\tstored), V16 (logging + error handling — `quota.delete` audit, generic 404 envelope, and the generic\n506\t`500` **fail-closed catch-all** for unexpected DB-I/O errors on both new verbs — 16.5.1/16.5.3,\n507\tAC19).\n508\t\n509\t**`n/a`:** V3 (server-to-server API, no browser HTML/cookies), V5 (no file handling), V7 (no\n510\tsessions — stateless API keys), V9 (no JWT/self-contained tokens), V10 (no OAuth/OIDC), V11 (no new\n511\tcrypto surface — Argon2id key hashing unchanged), V15 (no new concurrency-integrity guarantee — the\n512\tDELETE-vs-ingest race is an explicitly accepted risk, not an enforced invariant this slice), V17 (no\n513\tWebRTC).\n514\t\n515\t**In-scope L3:**\n516\t- **V8.2.x — object-level authorization rigor (IDOR/BOLA).** Justification: DELETE is a destructive\n517\t  cross-tenant-sensitive operation on a multi-tenant store; \"a key can neither see nor delete another\n518\t  tenant's quota\" is breach-critical for a metering product, delivered by the `api_key_id` filter +\n519\t  FORCE RLS and proven by the cross-tenant-DELETE→404 integration test (AC8).\n520\t\n521\t**Waivers:** none for triggered L1/L2 code/config items (the feature's surface is covered by the\n522\treused mechanisms above). Chapter `X.1` documentation items are advisory (org-level), not blocking.\n523\t\n524\t## Acceptance criteria trace (PROJECT.md / CLAUDE.md \"What done means\")\n525\t\n526\t- **Smoke check passes** → ✓ *Backend* / *Infrastructure*: no change to `/health` or app startup; the\n527\t  new handlers mount on the existing router; deferred DB/Redis init preserved.\n528\t- **Security report clean** → ✓ *Threat Model* + *ASVS Compliance* (parameterized DELETE SQL, admin\n529\t  gate, read/delete tenant isolation + FORCE RLS, minimal GET response, generic 404 envelope, and the\n530\t  safe-error / fail-closed generic 500 envelope on both DB-I/O paths); AC9, AC15, AC18, AC19.\n531\t- **Tests pass at >= 85% coverage** → ✓ *Test strategy* + `acceptance.md` (every AC maps to a named\n532\t  test; unit for the schema contract, integration for the Postgres-only ordering/tenancy guarantees).\n533\t- **Docs updated for touched directories** → ✓ *Files affected* (system_architecture.md + per-dir\n534\t  READMEs + CLAUDE.md, at the documentation stage).\n535\t- **PR description written** → handled by the documentation stage (out of planning's hands; noted).\n536\t- **pipeline-ci green (required merge check)** → ✓ *CI*: this feature adds no workflow and no new job;\n537\t  it must keep the existing `pipeline-ci.yml` jobs (lint, tests+coverage, security scan) green. The\n538\t  new tests run under the same suite; no CI configuration change is planned.\n539\t\n540\t## Revision notes\n541\t\n542\tSingle plan-audit revision pass (`.pipeline/plan-audit.md`, `revision_recommended: true`). One\n543\tmaterial flag, addressed:\n544\t\n545\t- **[material] No safe-error-handling (ASVS-DET T2-2) criterion for GET/DELETE `/v1/quotas`.** Both\n546\t  handlers do live DB I/O that can raise server-side, and the project has an exact precedent\n547\t  (`tests/integration/test_events_endpoint.py::test_forced_internal_error_returns_safe_envelope_and_fails_closed`,\n548\t  feature 1's AC19). Resolved — **not** waived as N/A, because the flag is correct (a forced DB\n549\t  exception on GET/DELETE would otherwise be unverified for leak/partial-state). Changes made:\n550\t  1. Added **AC19** to `.pipeline/acceptance.md` (a real, test-backed criterion — *not* delegated):\n551\t     a forced internal error on the GET list read and on the DELETE path returns the generic\n552\t     `500 internal` envelope (no stack/SQL/type/path leak), and the DELETE **fails closed** (the\n553\t     `scoped_transaction` rollback leaves the target row intact). Named the two integration tests in\n554\t     `tests/integration/test_quotas_list_delete.py`, mirroring the events precedent shape\n555\t     (monkeypatch the repo fn to raise, `ASGITransport(raise_app_exceptions=False)`).\n556\t  2. Bumped `.pipeline/acceptance.md` frontmatter `criteria_total: 18 → 19`; `delegated_criteria`\n557\t     unchanged (`[AC18]` — AC19 is test-backed, not delegated). Added a notes line explaining AC19's\n558\t     provenance, and recorded ASVS-DET T2-2 in `derived_from`.\n559\t  3. Added plan coverage in **`## API edge`** (a new \"Safe-error handling / fail-closed (AC19)\"\n560\t     bullet naming the `handle_unexpected_error` catch-all + the `scoped_transaction` rollback), in\n561\t     **`## Logging`** (the reused `request.unhandled_error` server-side log), in the **`## Test\n562\t     strategy`** integration list, and in the **`## Files affected`** description of the new\n563\t     integration test.\n564\t  4. Added a **STRIDE** Information-Disclosure row (GET/DELETE DB I/O boundary; Medium; generic-500\n565\t     catch-all + txn rollback; ASVS 16.5.1/16.5.3), added the matching line to the **copy-paste\n566\t     visualization prompt**, annotated the **Mermaid DFD** with the error boundary + rollback edge,\n567\t     and extended the **ASVS V16** line to cite the 500 fail-closed catch-all.\n568\t  5. Updated the **Summary** net-new-surfaces list and the **Security report clean** acceptance trace\n569\t     to include AC19.\n570\t\n571\tNo other changes — all other audit dimensions read clean (completeness, ambiguity, proof-claim,\n572\tdependency), and scope was not expanded beyond resolving this flag.\n573\t"}]},"uuid":"04715511-c4d7-46a1-bfc6-e6c2fedae1f8","timestamp":"2026-07-10T03:53:07.645Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"55620138-170a-4a2f-be25-740636353074","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
