{"parentUuid":"16466c52-6360-4d5b-abb0-84d2bf34c36d","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa8d8d09b1b911247","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcshYBwz7KVSVqcaRMygv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01V46vhFPpoZWRRznr28rR8h","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\src\\api\\README.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":876,"cache_read_input_tokens":61250,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":876,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcshYB4Qa9yy8qAzt5YJr","attributionAgent":"documentation","type":"assistant","uuid":"8c9efc83-2ff8-4c8a-a719-84dfae7f1339","timestamp":"2026-07-10T03:53:22.725Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
{"parentUuid":"8c9efc83-2ff8-4c8a-a719-84dfae7f1339","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b6d534eb-f80d-405a-a05d-4c7eb6280654","agentId":"aa8d8d09b1b911247","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01V46vhFPpoZWRRznr28rR8h","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# src/api/\n2\t\n3\t## Purpose\n4\t\n5\tHTTP API layer: FastAPI route handlers, request/response schemas (Pydantic v2), error envelope boundary, and edge-concern middleware (request ID, security headers, CORS, body-size guards).\n6\t\n7\t## Modules\n8\t\n9\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n10\t|---|---|\n11\t| `routes/events.py` | `POST /v1/events` handler; calls `events_service.create_event`. |\n12\t| `routes/usage.py` | `GET /v1/usage` handler; calls `usage_service.get_usage`. |\n13\t| `routes/usage_export.py` | `GET /v1/usage/export` handler; two-phase pre-flight row-cap check (`usage_export_service.prepare_export`) then a `StreamingResponse` body (`usage_export_service.stream_export_csv`). Kept in its own module (not added to `usage.py`) so `GET /v1/usage`'s code path stays untouched. Declares explicit `responses=` OpenAPI metadata (200 `text/csv`, 422) since a `StreamingResponse` has no `response_model` to introspect. |\n14\t| `routes/quotas.py` | `PUT /v1/quotas` handler; composes auth -> Tier-2 throttle -> an `admin`-scope gate (403 `forbidden` otherwise) -> `quota_service.upsert_tenant_quota`. |\n15\t| `routes/health.py` | `GET /health` (liveness, no dependencies) and `GET /health/ready` (readiness, DB + migration check). |\n16\t| `schemas/events.py` | Pydantic models for POST /v1/events request and response; `extra='forbid'` contract enforcement. Also defines the `CustomerId`/`Metric` anchored-allowlist `constr` types reused by `schemas/usage.py` and `schemas/usage_export.py`. |\n17\t| `schemas/usage.py` | Pydantic models for GET /v1/usage request (query parameters) and response. |\n18\t| `schemas/usage_export.py` | `UsageExportQueryParams` for GET /v1/usage/export — optional `customer_id`/`metric`/`from`/`to` filters (`from` bound via a Pydantic alias to the `from_` field, since `from` is a Python keyword), the same `[now-90d, now+1h]` range bound as `usage.py`, `extra='forbid'`. |\n19\t| `schemas/quotas.py` | Pydantic models for PUT /v1/quotas request (`customer_id`, `metric`, `limit_per_window`, `extra='forbid'`) and response (echo shape). |\n20\t| `csv_export.py` | The CSV encoding facade for the export route: `EXPORT_HEADER`, `escape_csv_text_cell` (the OWASP CSV/formula-injection escape, applied at the encoding sink independent of upstream ingest validation), and the `format_window_start`/`format_total_quantity` value formatters. |\n21\t| `middleware.py` | Request-ID / trace-ID assignment, security headers (HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options), CORS (allows GET/POST/PUT). |\n22\t| `errors.py` | Error-envelope boundary: catches all unhandled exceptions and returns `{error:{code,message,requestId}}` with no stack/secret leakage. `AppError` lets a raised exception carry an explicit `app_code` (e.g. `quota_exceeded`) that overrides the default status->code map — needed because 429 is shared by two distinct codes (`rate_limited` vs `quota_exceeded`). |\n23\t\n24\t## Relationships\n25\t\n26\t**Public surface:**\n27\t- Imported by `src/main.py` to register routes with FastAPI.\n28\t- Exposes `create_app()` function (in `src/main.py`) which returns the fully-configured FastAPI instance.\n29\t\n30\t**Dependencies:**\n31\t- `middleware.py` and `errors.py` are registered once at app construction (middleware stack + exception handler).\n32\t- Each route handler uses `require_api_key` guard from `src/auth` to enforce authentication.\n33\t- Route handlers call `src/services.{events_service, usage_service, usage_export_service}` to execute business logic.\n34\t- Schemas validate request bodies/parameters; malformed input raises Pydantic `ValidationError` → 422.\n35\t- Middleware and error boundary run for all routes, ensuring every response has proper headers and envelope shape.\n36\t- `routes/usage_export.py` and `services/usage_export_service.py` both import `csv_export.py` for the column contract and formula-escape (never inlined at either call site).\n37\t\n38\t**Middleware ordering (in `main.py`):**\n39\t1. Request-ID / trace (outermost) — sets correlation context for all downstream logging.\n40\t2. Security headers — applied to every response.\n41\t3. CORS — explicit allowlist from config.\n42\t4. Body-size guard — reject Content-Length > 8 KiB.\n43\t5. Tier-1 edge throttle (pre-auth) — IP+route keyed.\n44\t6. `require_api_key` guard — auth.\n45\t7. Tier-2 per-key throttle (post-auth) — api_key_id keyed.\n46\t8. Route handler (innermost) — wrapped by error-envelope boundary.\n47\t\n48\t## Notes\n49\t\n50\t**Contract enforcement:**\n51\t- Request bodies are validated against Pydantic schemas; `extra='forbid'` rejects unknown fields.\n52\t- All string fields are bounded length (e.g., `customer_id` ≤128, `metric` ≤64).\n53\t- `quantity` is a decimal > 0 (no zero or negative); `idempotency_key` is alphanumeric + underscore/dash.\n54\t- GET `/v1/usage` requires a timezone-aware ISO-8601 `window` parameter within 90 days past to 1 hour future (naive datetimes rejected).\n55\t- PUT `/v1/quotas`: `limit_per_window` is an integer `>= 1` (`<= 1e15`, BIGINT-safe); `customer_id`/`metric` reuse the same anchored allowlists as events; unknown fields (including a client-supplied `api_key_id`/`scope`) are rejected outright.\n56\t- GET `/v1/usage/export`: every filter (`customer_id`, `metric`, `from`, `to`) is optional; `from`/`to` follow the same timezone-aware, `[now-90d, now+1h]`-bounded contract as `usage.py`'s `window`, plus `from <= to`; unknown query params (including a client-supplied `api_key_id`) are rejected outright. A result exceeding 100,000 rows is rejected 422 *before* any response byte (a pre-flight `COUNT`, not a mid-stream cutoff).\n57\t\n58\t**Error handling:**\n59\t- Authentication failures (missing/invalid key) → 401/403 before handlers run.\n60\t- `PUT /v1/quotas` from a non-`admin`-scoped key → 403 `forbidden` (function-level authorization, checked in the route's composed dependency).\n61\t- Rate-limit exceeded (Tier-1 or Tier-2) → 429 `rate_limited` + Retry-After header.\n62\t- `POST /v1/events` over its quota → 429 `quota_exceeded` (distinct code, same status) + Retry-After to the next hour boundary; no event/rollup written (transaction rolled back).\n63\t- Schema validation failure → 422 with Pydantic error detail.\n64\t- Database errors (constraint violation, connection drop) → caught by error envelope → 500 (generic message, safe).\n65\t- Any unhandled exception → error envelope → 500, safe, no leak.\n66\t\n67\t**Security headers (all responses):**\n68\t- `Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains` (production only; localhost omitted).\n69\t- `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff` — disable MIME sniffing.\n70\t- `X-Frame-Options: DENY` — no embedding in iframes.\n71\t- `Cache-Control: no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate, max-age=0` (API, not HTML).\n72\t"}]},"uuid":"eba62888-36dc-45fe-a275-4f5b82760d50","timestamp":"2026-07-10T03:53:22.794Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"8c9efc83-2ff8-4c8a-a719-84dfae7f1339","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
{"parentUuid":"eba62888-36dc-45fe-a275-4f5b82760d50","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa8d8d09b1b911247","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcshYBwz7KVSVqcaRMygv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01NNLSBhjLqoKPxP2gp9U7qT","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\src\\repositories\\README.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":876,"cache_read_input_tokens":61250,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":876,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcshYB4Qa9yy8qAzt5YJr","attributionAgent":"documentation","type":"assistant","uuid":"466beb38-7b3a-4b65-a7af-28728032ff7c","timestamp":"2026-07-10T03:53:23.132Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
{"parentUuid":"466beb38-7b3a-4b65-a7af-28728032ff7c","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b6d534eb-f80d-405a-a05d-4c7eb6280654","agentId":"aa8d8d09b1b911247","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NNLSBhjLqoKPxP2gp9U7qT","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# src/repositories/\n2\t\n3\t## Purpose\n4\t\n5\tData access layer: SQL queries with parameterization, row-level scoping (by authenticated `api_key_id`), and minimal-field projections. All database I/O is encapsulated here.\n6\t\n7\t## Modules\n8\t\n9\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n10\t|---|---|\n11\t| `events_repo.py` | `insert_event_if_new(session, *, api_key_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, idempotency_key, window_start)` — `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, idempotency_key) DO NOTHING`, returning `None` on a duplicate. `find_event_by_idempotency_key(session, *, api_key_id, idempotency_key)` — reads back the original row on a duplicate replay. `increment_usage_rollup(session, *, api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window_start, quantity)` — the rollup upsert, called only after `insert_event_if_new` returns a row. |\n12\t| `usage_repo.py` | `find_usage_rollup(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window_start)` — SELECT from `usage_rollup` scoped by `api_key_id`. Returns None if missing (caller handles zero conversion). `count_usage_rollups(api_key_id, customer_id=None, metric=None, window_from=None, window_to=None)` — the export's pre-flight row-cap count over the same optional filters. `stream_usage_rollups(api_key_id, ..., limit)` — the export's server-side-cursor stream (`session.stream(...)`, yields `UsageRollupExportRecord`), ordered by a **fixed literal** `ORDER BY window_start, customer_id, metric` (never client-derived) with `LIMIT`. The count and stream queries share a `_export_filter_clause_and_params` helper so their WHERE clauses can never drift apart. |\n13\t| `api_keys_repo.py` | `find_active_key_by_key_id(key_id)` — SELECT from `api_keys` by public `key_id` (used by auth cache miss); returns the full row including `scope`. `create_api_key(..., scope=\"ingest\")` — the only key-provisioning path. |\n14\t| `quotas_repo.py` | `upsert_quota(...)` — `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, customer_id, metric) DO UPDATE ... RETURNING (xmax = 0) AS inserted`, reporting create-vs-replace in one round-trip. `read_tenant_quota_state_locked(...)` — the atomic check-then-decide: locks the quota row (`FOR UPDATE`), then reads the current-window rollup total as a **separate, fresh** statement (see *Notes* below for why). Returns `None` when no quota exists (unlimited, no lock taken). |\n15\t\n16\t## Relationships\n17\t\n18\t**Public surface:**\n19\t- Imported by `src/services.{events_service, usage_service, usage_export_service, quota_service}` to execute queries.\n20\t- `api_keys_repo` is also imported by `src/auth.api_key` (credential lookup on cache miss).\n21\t- `quotas_repo` is imported by both `quota_service` (the upsert) and `events_service` (the read-and-decide).\n22\t\n23\t**Dependencies:**\n24\t- All functions are async; they receive an `AsyncSession` from the service layer (obtained via `src/db.session_context`).\n25\t- Queries use SQLAlchemy ORM with bound parameters (no string concatenation); all user input is parameterized.\n26\t- RLS is set per-transaction by `src/db.session_context` before the first query runs (sets the `app.current_api_key_id` PostgreSQL context variable).\n27\t\n28\t**Row-level security:**\n29\t- Every query includes the authenticated `api_key_id` in the WHERE clause (primary application-layer control).\n30\t- E.g., `WHERE api_key_id = :auth_key AND customer_id = :customer_id` — no unscoped queries.\n31\t- PostgreSQL RLS policy (`USING (api_key_id = current_setting(...))`) is the backstop; the app role has no `BYPASSRLS`.\n32\t- If a query accidentally omits the `api_key_id` filter, RLS blocks it at the database level (defense-in-depth).\n33\t\n34\t**Field projections (minimal surface):**\n35\t- `insert_event_if_new` / `find_event_by_idempotency_key` return an `EventRecord{id, api_key_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, idempotency_key, window_start}` — the service layer maps this to the minimal public response shape (not the full row is a service-layer concern, not a repo-layer projection).\n36\t- `find_usage_rollup` returns only `{total_quantity, event_count}` — not internal bookkeeping (`updated_at`, `api_key_id`).\n37\t- `stream_usage_rollups` yields `UsageRollupExportRecord{customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity}` — exactly the four exported columns, never `event_count`, `updated_at`, or `api_key_id`.\n38\t- `api_keys_repo.get_by_key_id` returns the full row (needed by auth for `secret_hash`, `rate_limit_per_sec`, `revoked_at`).\n39\t\n40\t**Constraint enforcement:**\n41\t- `insert_event_if_new` relies on the `UNIQUE (api_key_id, idempotency_key)` constraint plus `ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING` (not a caught `IntegrityError`) — a duplicate insert returns no row, evaluated atomically by PostgreSQL. If no row is returned, the service calls `find_event_by_idempotency_key` to read the original row instead.\n42\t- `quantity > 0` and other domain constraints are enforced by CHECK constraints in the schema (verified at insert time).\n43\t\n44\t## Notes\n45\t\n46\t**ON CONFLICT pattern:**\n47\t- The idempotency mechanism uses `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, idempotency_key) DO NOTHING RETURNING id, ...`.\n48\t- If the unique constraint is violated, the INSERT returns no rows.\n49\t- The service layer checks `if result` — if a row was returned, this request won the insert; if not, a duplicate is detected.\n50\t\n51\t**RLS context setup:**\n52\t- Before any query, `src/db.session_context` sets `SET LOCAL app.current_api_key_id = :id` in the transaction.\n53\t- This context variable is read by the PostgreSQL RLS policy on every table access.\n54\t- The `SET LOCAL` is per-transaction (automatically cleared at commit), so no context leakage across requests.\n55\t\n56\t**Quota lock-then-read pattern (why it's two statements, not one):**\n57\t- `read_tenant_quota_state_locked` deliberately issues the `FOR UPDATE` lock on `quotas` and the `usage_rollup` read as two separate statements, not a single `LEFT JOIN ... FOR UPDATE OF q` query.\n58\t- PostgreSQL's `FOR UPDATE` only forces a fresh re-check (`EvalPlanQual`) of the *locked* row itself when a blocked waiter unblocks after the holder commits — it does **not** force a fresh snapshot for another table read in the same statement, including a joined one.\n59\t- A single combined statement lets a waiter that queued before the holder committed read `usage_rollup` from its own stale pre-wait snapshot — verified empirically during implementation: every concurrent waiter read the same stale total and all got admitted, silently breaking the cap.\n60\t- Issuing the `usage_rollup` read as its own statement *after* the lock is acquired gives it a fresh READ COMMITTED snapshot that does include everything the previous holder just committed — this is what makes `current_total` accurate for every waiter, not just the first uncontended caller (`tests/integration/test_quota_concurrency.py`).\n61\t\n62\t**Async pattern:**\n63\t- All functions are async; they use `await session.execute(...)` for queries.\n64\t- They receive an `AsyncSession` that's already connected and in a transaction (setup by `src/db.session_context`).\n65\t- No explicit connection management in the repo; the session is provided by the caller.\n66\t"}]},"uuid":"e0443fd7-8ffd-454f-b0db-a254d4c0dba5","timestamp":"2026-07-10T03:53:23.197Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"466beb38-7b3a-4b65-a7af-28728032ff7c","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
