{"parentUuid":"958ca78b-a39e-4cfd-8f70-e5e8ec75b8ad","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa8d8d09b1b911247","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcshYyFHDNNn7pEjW1JD3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01HHgBwc6tzWFEJ3ZyWrFSip","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\docs\\system_architecture.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2452,"cache_read_input_tokens":74547,"output_tokens":231,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2452},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":231,"cache_read_input_tokens":74547,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2452,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2452,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcshYxFzoqt6YofMj2cUH","attributionAgent":"documentation","type":"assistant","uuid":"a870df8e-0bf5-4418-8cb2-6382bebfc375","timestamp":"2026-07-10T03:53:34.562Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
{"parentUuid":"a870df8e-0bf5-4418-8cb2-6382bebfc375","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b6d534eb-f80d-405a-a05d-4c7eb6280654","agentId":"aa8d8d09b1b911247","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HHgBwc6tzWFEJ3ZyWrFSip","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Meterly — system architecture\n2\t\n3\t## Overview\n4\t\n5\tMeterly ingests metered usage events, serves aggregated per-customer/metric\n6\tcounters (single-bucket read or a streamed CSV export), and enforces\n7\tadmin-set per-customer, per-metric usage caps (\"quotas\"). Four authenticated\n8\tHTTP endpoints, one PostgreSQL database, one Redis rate-limit store, running\n9\tas a Docker container on ECS Fargate behind an ALB.\n10\t\n11\t```\n12\tClient --HTTPS+API key--> ALB --> FastAPI (ECS Fargate, >=2 tasks)\n13\t                                     |-- Tier-1 (IP) / Tier-2 (api_key_id) throttle --> Redis\n14\t                                     |-- bound-parameter SQL, RLS-scoped -------------> RDS PostgreSQL\n15\t                                     |-- DB credential fetch ------------------------> Secrets Manager\n16\t                                     |-- traces/logs/errors -------------------------> CloudWatch/X-Ray/Sentry\n17\t```\n18\t\n19\t```mermaid\n20\tflowchart LR\n21\t    Client[Client] -->|\"HTTPS + API key\"| ALB[ALB]\n22\t    ALB --> FastAPI[\"FastAPI (ECS Fargate, >=2 tasks)\"]\n23\t    FastAPI -->|\"Tier-1 IP+route / Tier-2 api_key_id throttle\"| Redis[(Redis)]\n24\t    FastAPI -->|\"require_api_key: cache hit or Argon2id verify\"| AuthDB[(RDS PostgreSQL: api_keys)]\n25\t    FastAPI -->|\"POST /v1/events: insert + quota check + rollup upsert\"| EventsDB[(RDS PostgreSQL: events / usage_rollup / quotas)]\n26\t    FastAPI -->|\"GET /v1/usage: read rollup\"| EventsDB\n27\t    FastAPI -->|\"GET /v1/usage/export: pre-flight COUNT + streamed SELECT\"| EventsDB\n28\t    FastAPI -->|\"PUT /v1/quotas: upsert cap\"| EventsDB\n29\t    FastAPI -->|\"DB credential fetch\"| Secrets[Secrets Manager]\n30\t    FastAPI -->|\"traces/logs/errors\"| Observability[\"CloudWatch / X-Ray / Sentry\"]\n31\t```\n32\t\n33\t## Request flow — `POST /v1/events`\n34\t\n35\t1. Request-id/trace assigned, security headers queued (`src/logging/middleware.py`, `src/api/middleware.py`).\n36\t2. Tier-1 IP+route throttle (Redis token bucket; fails open on a Redis outage).\n37\t3. `require_api_key` — split-token parse, in-process verification-cache check,\n38\t   falling back to a DB lookup + Argon2id verify on a cache miss\n39\t   (`src/auth/__init__.py`, `src/auth/api_key.py`).\n40\t4. Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` throttle (`src/auth/rate_limit.py`).\n41\t5. Pydantic schema validation (`src/api/schemas/events.py`) — anchored\n42\t   allowlists, `extra='forbid'`.\n43\t6. `events_service.create_event` — one transaction:\n44\t   `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, idempotency_key) DO NOTHING`, and only\n45\t   if a row was inserted:\n46\t   - the quota check: `read_tenant_quota_state_locked` locks the caller's\n47\t     quota row for `(customer, metric)` (if one exists) and reads the\n48\t     current-window rollup total fresh; if `R + Q > L` the service raises\n49\t     `QuotaExceededError` (429 `quota_exceeded`, `Retry-After` to the next\n50\t     hour boundary), which propagates out of the transaction and rolls back\n51\t     the event insert — no partial write, no rollup increment\n52\t     (`src/services/events_service.py`, `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`).\n53\t   - otherwise, `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO UPDATE` the `usage_rollup`\n54\t     counter (`src/repositories/events_repo.py`).\n55\t   A duplicate `idempotency_key` (replay) never reaches the quota check at\n56\t   all — only the winning-insert branch does.\n57\t7. Error-envelope boundary catches anything unhandled and returns the generic\n58\t   `{error:{code,message,requestId}}` shape (`src/api/errors.py`); `AppError`\n59\t   lets a handler attach an explicit `app_code` (e.g. `quota_exceeded`) that\n60\t   overrides the default status->code map, so two different 429s\n61\t   (`rate_limited` vs. `quota_exceeded`) stay distinguishable to the caller.\n62\t\n63\t## Request flow — `GET /v1/usage`\n64\t\n65\tSame auth/throttle/error stack; the service floors `window` to the UTC hour\n66\tand reads a single `usage_rollup` row scoped by the caller's `api_key_id`\n67\t(`src/services/usage_service.py`, `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`). A missing\n68\tbucket returns zeros with 200, never 404.\n69\t\n70\t## Request flow — `GET /v1/usage/export`\n71\t\n72\tSame auth/throttle/error stack, plus a two-phase pre-flight-then-stream\n73\tdesign (`src/api/routes/usage_export.py`,\n74\t`src/services/usage_export_service.py`,\n75\t`src/repositories/usage_repo.py`):\n76\t\n77\t1. `UsageExportQueryParams` validates the optional `customer_id`/`metric`/\n78\t   `from`/`to` filters (`src/api/schemas/usage_export.py`) — reuses the same\n79\t   `CustomerId`/`Metric` anchored allowlists as `events.py` and the same\n80\t   `[now-90d, now+1h]` bound idiom as `usage.py`'s `window`, applied here to\n81\t   a `[from, to]` range.\n82\t2. **Pre-flight cap check** (`prepare_export`): a `COUNT(*)` over the\n83\t   caller's rows (scoped by `api_key_id` first, plus the optional filters)\n84\t   inside its own transaction. Over 100,000 rows -> 422\n85\t   `validation_failed`, logged at `warn` (`usage.export.rejected`). This\n86\t   runs, and fully resolves, *before* any response byte — once a\n87\t   `StreamingResponse` is constructed the status line is already 200 and the\n88\t   cap decision can no longer cleanly 422. Any *other* (non-cap) error here\n89\t   propagates uncaught to the error-envelope boundary: a fail-closed generic\n90\t   500, transaction rolled back, no stream ever started.\n91\t3. **Stream** (`stream_export_csv`): a `StreamingResponse` whose body\n92\t   generator is pulled by Starlette only after the handler returns, so it\n93\t   opens its **own** tenant-scoped transaction (the `SET LOCAL\n94\t   app.current_api_key_id` RLS-backstop setting and the server-side cursor\n95\t   both need to stay valid for the whole stream, not just the pre-flight\n96\t   phase). Yields the header row first, always (an empty result is a 200\n97\t   header-only CSV, never 404), then one CSV-encoded row per record from\n98\t   `stream_usage_rollups` (`ORDER BY window_start, customer_id, metric` — a\n99\t   fixed literal, never client-derived — `LIMIT 100000`), each row written\n100\t   into a reused `io.StringIO` via stdlib `csv.writer` (RFC 4180, CRLF,\n101\t   `QUOTE_MINIMAL`) and drained to bytes immediately — constant memory\n102\t   throughout. `customer_id`/`metric` text cells pass through\n103\t   `src/api/csv_export.py`'s `escape_csv_text_cell` (the OWASP\n104\t   formula-injection defense: a leading `= + - @ \\t \\r` gets a `'` prefix)\n105\t   *before* reaching the writer; numeric/timestamp cells are formatted but\n106\t   never escaped (they're server-generated, never attacker-controlled).\n107\t   Logs exactly one `usage.export` audit event in a `finally` block\n108\t   (`rowCount`, `capped`, `completed`, filter-presence booleans — never the\n109\t   raw `customer_id`/`metric` values), so a client disconnect or a mid-stream\n110\t   DB error still records what was actually sent.\n111\t\n112\tResponse headers: `Content-Type: text/csv; charset=utf-8`,\n113\t`Content-Disposition: attachment; filename=\"usage-export-<UTC\n114\ttimestamp>.csv\"` (no tenant identifier in the filename), plus the inherited\n115\t`nosniff` and (via the existing `/v1/usage`-prefix rule in\n116\t`src/api/middleware.py`) `Cache-Control: no-store`.\n117\t\n118\t**Accepted risk — mid-stream failure truncates the CSV.** Once the 200\n119\tstatus line and header bytes are on the wire, an unhandled error partway\n120\tthrough the stream can no longer be converted to a clean error envelope; the\n121\tclient sees a truncated download it can re-request. This is strictly the\n122\t*post-200* case — the pre-flight `COUNT` phase above is fully recoverable\n123\tand does return the generic 500 envelope. Bounded by the row cap + Tier-2\n124\tthrottle + connection-pool sizing; batched keyset pagination is the future\n125\tmitigation if this needs closing further.\n126\t\n127\t## Request flow — `PUT /v1/quotas`\n128\t\n129\tAdmin-scoped create-or-replace of a per-customer, per-metric usage cap.\n130\tAuth -> Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` throttle -> an `admin`-scope assertion in the\n131\troute's composed dependency (403 `forbidden` for a non-admin key) -> schema\n132\tvalidation (`src/api/schemas/quotas.py`) -> `upsert_tenant_quota`, a single\n133\t`INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, customer_id, metric) DO UPDATE ...\n134\tRETURNING (xmax = 0) AS inserted` that reports create-vs-replace in one\n135\tround-trip (201 create / 200 replace), with a `quota.upsert` audit log\n136\t(`src/api/routes/quotas.py`, `src/services/quota_service.py`,\n137\t`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`).\n138\t\n139\t## Data model\n140\t\n141\t- `api_keys` — the tenant/credential table (migration 0001), extended with a\n142\t  `scope` column (migration 0003: `'ingest'` default, `'admin'` elevated).\n143\t  `secret_hash` is Argon2id; `key_id` is the public split-token lookup\n144\t  handle. `scope='admin'` is a superset scope — an admin key does everything\n145\t  an ingest key does, plus call `PUT /v1/quotas`; a tenant that wants quotas\n146\t  provisions one admin-scoped key and uses it for both.\n147\t- `events` — append-only ingest log (migration 0001). `UNIQUE (api_key_id,\n148\t  idempotency_key)` is the idempotency guarantee; RLS policy\n149\t  `events_tenant_isolation` is the application-scoping backstop.\n150\t- `usage_rollup` — derived hourly aggregate (migration 0002, expand +\n151\t  backfill from `events`). Composite PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric,\n152\t  window_start)`; RLS policy `usage_rollup_tenant_isolation`.\n153\t- `quotas` — per-tenant, per-customer, per-metric usage caps (migration\n154\t  0003). PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric)`; `CHECK (limit_per_window >=\n155\t  1)`; RLS policy `quotas_tenant_isolation`. The `POST /v1/events` quota\n156\t  check takes `FOR UPDATE` on this row to serialize concurrent writers for\n157\t  the same `(customer, metric)` — see *Quota enforcement / atomicity* below.\n158\t\n159\t## Quota enforcement / atomicity\n160\t\n161\tStrict enforcement (\"usage can never exceed `L`\") is a check-then-act on a\n162\tshared counter — the classic TOCTOU. `read_tenant_quota_state_locked`\n163\t(`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`) makes it race-free with a `SELECT\n164\tlimit_per_window ... FOR UPDATE` on the quota row, run **as a separate\n165\tstatement from the subsequent `usage_rollup` read**, both inside the same\n166\ttransaction as the event insert and rollup increment\n167\t(`src/services/events_service.py`).\n168\t\n169\tThis two-round-trip shape is deliberate, not incidental: PostgreSQL's `FOR\n170\tUPDATE` only guarantees a fresh re-check of the *locked* row itself when a\n171\twaiter unblocks after the lock holder commits — it does **not** force a\n172\tfresh snapshot for another table read in the same statement (e.g. a `LEFT\n173\tJOIN` to `usage_rollup`). A waiter queued before the holder committed would\n174\tevaluate that join against its own pre-wait snapshot and read a stale total,\n175\tsilently letting concurrent writers jointly exceed the cap. Splitting the\n176\tlock-acquire and the rollup-read into two statements gives the second query\n177\tits own fresh READ COMMITTED snapshot (taken *after* the lock is held),\n178\twhich does reflect everything the previous holder just committed. This was\n179\tverified empirically during implementation: a single combined\n180\t`LEFT JOIN ... FOR UPDATE OF q` statement let every concurrent waiter read\n181\tthe same stale total and all get admitted; the two-statement version\n182\tcorrectly serializes and caps admission at `L`\n183\t(`tests/integration/test_quota_concurrency.py`).\n184\t\n185\tUnlimited customers (no quota row) take no lock at all — the first `SELECT\n186\t... FOR UPDATE` simply matches zero rows, so the common, zero-contention\n187\tpath stays cheap (AC20 measures its added latency under load).\n188\t\n189\t## Auth\n190\t\n191\tSplit-token API keys (`mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>`), Argon2id-hashed at rest.\n192\tAn in-process, TTL-bounded verification cache (keyed on the public `key_id`,\n193\tguarded by a constant-time digest comparison) avoids paying the Argon2id cost\n194\ton every request while the durable store stays Argon2id-only. See\n195\t`src/auth/__init__.py` for the full tradeoff writeup and\n196\t`scripts/seed_api_key.py` for the only key-provisioning path (no HTTP\n197\tendpoint in this build's scope; pass `--admin` to provision a `scope='admin'`\n198\tkey for `PUT /v1/quotas`, including the DAST-context admin test key, DAST-3).\n199\t\n200\t## Rate limiting\n201\t\n202\tTwo Redis token-bucket tiers (`src/auth/rate_limit.py`): Tier-1 pre-auth,\n203\tkeyed on IP+route; Tier-2 post-auth, keyed on the authenticated\n204\t`api_key_id`. Both fail open (log a warning, allow the request) on a Redis\n205\tconnection error rather than failing every request — an availability\n206\ttradeoff recorded in `.pipeline/surface-delta.md`.\n207\t\n208\t## Observability\n209\t\n210\tStructured JSON logs (structlog) to stdout -> CloudWatch, with a centralized\n211\tredaction processor (`src/logging/__init__.py`). OTel traces -> ADOT sidecar\n212\t-> X-Ray; Sentry for release-tagged error tracking with a `before_send`\n213\tPII/secret scrubber (`src/observability/`). SLO burn-rate alarms and the\n214\tminimum-three canary alarms are declared in `infra/modules/observability`.\n215\t\n216\t## Infrastructure\n217\t\n218\tTerraform under `infra/`: `modules/{network,compute,data,observability,edge}`\n219\thold the real resources; `envs/{staging,prod}/main.tf` are the two\n220\tself-contained deploy roots (own provider + backend, since Terraform only\n221\tpermits a backend configuration in a root module) that instantiate the same\n222\tmodules at different scale. See each module's file header comments for the\n223\tspecific resources and the security-baseline items they satisfy\n224\t(encryption at rest, private subnets, least-privilege IAM, no `BYPASSRLS`).\n225\t\n226\t## Known deviations / accepted risks\n227\t\n228\tSee `.pipeline/surface-delta.md` for the rate-limit fail-open behavior and the\n229\tOTel/Sentry wiring-at-construction-time change vs. the plan's original\n230\tlifespan-hook placement. See `plan.md`'s \"Open questions\" section for the\n231\taccepted risks around key-revocation latency, `api_key_id`-as-tenant-scope,\n232\tand the Postgres app-role bootstrap's CI-network-reachability prerequisite.\n233\t\n234\t**`GET /v1/usage/export` p95 at the 100,000-row cap — resolved (was: plan\n235\t§\"Open questions\" #1, originally unconfirmed).** The first measured p95\n236\t(~10.7s locally / 25.2s on testing's independent re-measure) was root-caused\n237\tduring debugging to the streaming generator yielding **one chunk per row**:\n238\tthe app's four nested `BaseHTTPMiddleware` layers (`src/main.py`) each\n239\tre-pump every streamed chunk through their own anyio memory-object-stream, so\n240\tcost scaled with `chunk_count x middleware_layers` and dominated wall-clock\n241\ttime at the 100k-row cap — not CSV encoding or DB query time, which were both\n242\tsub-second in isolation. Three within-design fixes closed the gap (see\n243\t`.pipeline/debug-notes.md` for the full isolation profiling):\n244\t- `src/services/usage_export_service.py` batches `_ROWS_PER_CHUNK = 1000`\n245\t  encoded rows per yielded chunk (was one row per chunk) — the primary lever,\n246\t  cutting chunk count ~1,000x at the cap while staying constant-memory (the\n247\t  buffer holds at most one batch).\n248\t- `src/api/csv_export.py`'s `escape_csv_text_cell` replaced its per-character\n249\t  strip loop with a precompiled `str.translate` deletion table (semantics\n250\t  verified identical across all C0/DEL codepoints).\n251\t- `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`'s `stream_usage_rollups` tunes the\n252\t  server-side cursor with `execution_options(yield_per=_STREAM_FETCH_BATCH)`\n253\t  (`_STREAM_FETCH_BATCH = 5000`) — more rows fetched per DB round-trip,\n254\t  cursor still never abandoned.\n255\t\n256\tNet effect: p95 dropped from ~10.7s to a stable **p95 ~1.6-2.1s** (10-sample\n257\tmeasurement). The original 500ms target proved unreachable within the\n258\tapproved constant-memory-streaming design (an irreducible ~0.85-1.0s floor\n259\tfrom the server-side cursor drain + per-row CSV encoding, even discounting\n260\tmiddleware). The human confirmed a revised, binding budget of **p95 <=\n261\t3,000ms at the 100,000-row cap** at the 2026-07-09 escalation, which\n262\t`tests/integration/test_usage_export_perf.py` now hard-asserts (AC16); this\n263\tsession's re-run measured p95 1,643.87ms, comfortably under the bound.\n264\t"}]},"uuid":"624ae831-66e1-431a-884b-e61611f97330","timestamp":"2026-07-10T03:53:34.592Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"a870df8e-0bf5-4418-8cb2-6382bebfc375","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
